Rating: 4
This recipe turned out excellent enchilladas using some variation. I made my own enchillada sauce courtesy of: Valerie (groovbunie@aol.com) Enchilada Sauce - Emeril Lagasse 3 tablespoons vegetable oil 1 tablespoon flour 1/4 cup chili powder (or a little less) 2 cups chicken stock 10 ounces tomato paste 1 teaspoon dried oregano 1 teaspoon ground cumin 1/2 teaspoon salt In a medium saucepan heat oil, add flour, smoothing and stirring with a wooden spoon. Cook for 1 minute. Add chili powder and cook for 30 seconds. Add stock, tomato paste, oregano, and cumin. Stir to combine. Bring to a boil, reduce heat to low and cook for 15 minutes. The sauce will thicken and smooth out. I also poached the chicken in water with chopped onion, cumin, oregano, basil, cayenne pepper, minced garlic and cilantro. I toasted my corn tortillas at 350F for 5 minutes for flavor and to crunch them up a bit. I then stuffed the tortillas with the chicken mix, pepper sautee, cheese, and a dash of the enchillada sauce and baked as recommended. Muy Bueno!

Rating: 1
The over all taste wasn't terrible. The problem was pouring the sauce over the enchiladas and baking. The tortillas become soaked, soft and mushy during baking - it was almost impossible to get them out of the baking dish without them falling apart. I asked a Hispanic friend of mine from El Paso, TX what the problem was as this is his native cuisine. His advice was that the sauce should not be poured over the enchiladas before baking. He said his mother would heat the tortillas on a very hot dry cast iron skillet (turning as they darken slightly) rather than frying them (enchiladas are not "tacos" he said). Then each tortilla should be "dipped" in the sauce just to coat each side. Stuff the enchiladas with the filling as directed and roll up (he said everyone makes their filling a little different so this one is fine - he zips it up a bit with cilantro and a jalapeno). Anyway, bake the enchiladas as directed. Place serving portions on plates and pour the sauce over the enchiladas just before serving. Place extra sauce on the table. I tried this and it was much better. The texture of the tortillas was not mushy they held up very well and tasted great.

Rating: 4
This recipe was very tasty and devoured by a crowd at a potluck. I poached the chicken in broth & herbs to help keep it moist. Also adding cumin and some chopped green chilis to the pepper saute gave it extra flavor. I also found a good recipe for enchilada sauce that is not much more difficult than opening a can and certainly tastier! Enjoy~ Easy Enchilada Sauce - Emeril Lagasse 3 tablespoons vegetable oil 1 tablespoon flour 1/4 cup chili powder (or a little less) 2 cups chicken stock 10 ounces tomato paste 1 teaspoon dried oregano 1 teaspoon ground cumin 1/2 teaspoon salt In a medium saucepan heat oil, add flour, smoothing and stirring with a wooden spoon. Cook for 1 minute. Add chili powder and cook for 30 seconds. Add stock, tomato paste, oregano, and cumin. Stir to combine. Bring to a boil, reduce heat to low and cook for 15 minutes. The sauce will thicken and smooth out. Yield: 2 1/2 cups of sauce

